\f2\i \cf2 ANTONY, OCTAVIUS, and LEPIDUS, seated at a table
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 ANTONY\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 These many, then, shall die; their names are prick'd.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 OCTAVIUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 Your brother too must die; consent you, Lepidus?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 LEPIDUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 I do consent--\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 OCTAVIUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 Prick him down, Antony.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 LEPIDUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 Upon condition Publius shall not live,\
Who is your sister's son, Mark Antony.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 ANTONY\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 He shall not live; look, with a spot I damn him.\
But, Lepidus, go you to Caesar's house;\
Fetch the will hither, and we shall determine\
How to cut off some charge in legacies.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 LEPIDUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 What, shall I find you here?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 OCTAVIUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 Or here, or at the Capitol.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf2 Exit LEPIDUS
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 ANTONY\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 This is a slight unmeritable man,\
Meet to be sent on errands: is it fit,\
The three-fold world divided, he should stand\
One of the three to share it?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 OCTAVIUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 So you thought him;\
And took his voice who should be prick'd to die,\
In our black sentence and proscription.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 ANTONY\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 Octavius, I have seen more days than you:\
And though we lay these honours on this man,\
To ease ourselves of divers slanderous loads,\
He shall but bear them as the ass bears gold,\
To groan and sweat under the business,\
Either led or driven, as we point the way;\
And having brought our treasure where we will,\
Then take we down his load, and turn him off,\
Like to the empty ass, to shake his ears,\
And graze in commons.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 OCTAVIUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 You may do your will;\
But he's a tried and valiant soldier.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 ANTONY\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 So is my horse, Octavius; and for that\
I do appoint him store of provender:\
It is a creature that I teach to fight,\
To wind, to stop, to run directly on,\
His corporal motion govern'd by my spirit.\
And, in some taste, is Lepidus but so;\
He must be taught and train'd and bid go forth;\
A barren-spirited fellow; one that feeds\
On abjects, orts and imitations,\
Which, out of use and staled by other men,\
Begin his fashion: do not talk of him,\
But as a property. And now, Octavius,\
Listen great things:--Brutus and Cassius\
Are levying powers: we must straight make head:\
Therefore let our alliance be combined,\
Our best friends made, our means stretch'd\
And let us presently go sit in council,\
How covert matters may be best disclosed,\
And open perils surest answered.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 OCTAVIUS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 Let us do so: for we are at the stake,\
And bay'd about with many enemies;\
And some that smile have in their hearts, I fear,\
Millions of mischiefs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf2 Exeunt
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

